figgy.title: DaoUpdateJob fails when an archival object is not found

comments.body: This is a little different from #4761 - there's a bunch of Lapidus records whose IDs look like component IDs, but they're not - they're just stuff that should be in title. If an archival object isn't found it should just silently fail.

Another example of this issue is C0140_c73270-52667, which has a REF ID of C0140_c73270-52667 but a component ID of C0140_c03432. FIggy's pointed at C0140_c03432, but can't find the archival object because the ref ID is different. I'm not sure if this is something we can handle or if in this case they just need to fix it in aspace. Hopefully @faithc will know.

Query: https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/eefadfca0d6df08a78fdc22871063f7b96b7337b/app/services/aspace/client.rb#L29

pulfalight.title: Viewer should search for the ID that's in the EAD, not the solr record ID
dash vs dot in older figgy records not showing online content

comments.body:
So the ID in Pulfalight was changed in the URL, but the actual call numbers still have periods in them. 

For example: https://aspace.princeton.edu/staff/resources/2161#tree::archival_object_733628 The call number for this is AC107.07_c897. If you put that in Figgy it works fine.

In fact, if you use the "-" version (which is only in the pulfalight URL) in Figgy then I think DAO updating wouldn't work, since it'd try to find the archival object and not find it (there's no "AC107-07_c897"). 

So I think there's a few things to do here:

1. Update all instances of "-" in Figgy with "." (this should only be new records I think?)
2. Update the Pulfalight javascript that looks up the viewer to use periods instead of dashes.
3. If a user enters a "-" and it finds a record whose actual call number is "." it should use that as the source metadata identifier.

On the bright side I think there's only 15 resources in Figgy that have the "dash instead of period":

```sql
figgy_production=# select id, metadata->'source_metadata_identifier'->>0 FROM orm_resources WHERE metadata @> '{"source_metadata_identifier": []}' AND metadata->'source_metadata_identifier'->>0 LIKE '%-%\_%' AND metadata->'source_metadata_identifier'->>0 NOT LIKE '%.%';
                  id                  |       ?column?
--------------------------------------+-----------------------
 db638171-5856-451d-a323-cf2a9414217b | AC105-03_c3166
 8017bdb4-a9e7-4cce-9474-39c90e1fbf96 | AC105-04_c149
 055754ce-789d-4e71-aea5-e76dd4c042bb | AC107-06_c340
 1cbeb7b2-c379-4657-9102-df8ec6943bfb | RCPXG-5830371-2_c0528
 b2f92225-3835-4445-94f2-d244400daf1c | AC104-03_c2
 d40d3ede-7eef-405e-955f-8103b6eff6fc | AC198-03_c1536
 06b00c73-a596-4ecf-93cb-da052c8fa875 | AC198-04_c3932
 06746e41-aa46-41e2-8994-8109051a9af2 | AC104-03_c6158
 88a81495-718d-41e9-9534-d19c5ddc4e91 | AC107-14_c1223
 ad0046c2-f183-41ff-8277-2e668df453ad | AC198-02_c610
 150e0667-9a69-46b8-8aea-66d3c61aa707 | AC107-10_c3187
 ec23d20b-a52d-4687-9ab6-f3f42d6b0f97 | AC105-02_c147
 c667b46f-c069-4f58-959a-99a2a967855f | AC198-03_c698
 86f45dd2-1e75-4a0d-a381-4a411ac39641 | AC105-04_c4644
 2fb9377d-f556-4d94-a2a7-e4d490eac9e1 | AC104-03_c1338
(15 rows)
```

> In fact, if you use the "-" version (which is only in the pulfalight URL) in Figgy then I think DAO updating wouldn't work, since it'd try to find the archival object and not find it (there's no "AC107-07_c897").

Figgy isn't searching by ID?

> Many collections that previously had a . in the collection number and now have a - 

So I read this ticket initially as saying that IDs had been changed in aspace. I think what @tpendragon is saying is that's not the case, that the only change was made in pulfalight for the purposes of having url-safe characters in the url. It sounds like we will keep the url that way but not use that form for anything else.

I think an ADR would be helpful here.

pulfalight.title: delete_all_searches task triggered a postgres deadlock

comments.body:
This is a cron task installed by princeton_ansible on all `blacklight_app` boxes: https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/main/roles/blacklight_app/tasks/main.yml

It's weird we're only seeing it for Pulfalight though, I'd expect it for Orangelight, pulmap, and LAE as well.

The ansible-installed task was not working on orangelight and when I went to run it manually it crashed because of memory problems. I reimplemented the cleanup so it didn't load all the users in memory before starting to delete them.

Relevant PRs:
- https://github.com/pulibrary/orangelight/pull/2457/files
- https://github.com/pulibrary/orangelight/pull/2484/files

I put this in place on orangelight and DSS. Following through on all the apps that use the ansible-installed task and then removing it would good, either by submitting an upstream PR or by touching all the apps directly.
